<exercise checkit-seed="0003" checkit-slug="FO4" checkit-title="Exact First-Order IVPs">
  <statement>
    <p>
        Explain why one of the following ODEs is exact, and why the other is not.
    </p>
      <me>-2 \, t^{2} {y'} + y^{2} = -2 \, t^{2} y {y'} - 16 \, t^{3} + t {y'}</me><me>y^{2} - y = -16 \, t^{3} - 2 \, t y {y'} + t {y'}</me>
    <p>
      Then find an implicit solution for the exact ODE
      that satisfies the initial value
        <m>y(1)=-1</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <answer>
    <p>The following ODE is exact.</p>
      <me>y^{2} - y = -16 \, t^{3} - 2 \, t y {y'} + t {y'}</me>
    <p>
      Its implicit solution satisfying the initial value is:
    </p>
      <me>4 \, t^{4} + t y^{2} - t y = 6</me>
  </answer>
</exercise>
